    <!-- LEAD SUMMARY -->
    <p><strong>Washington</strong> - President Trump faced a critical legal challenge to his travel ban as federal appeals court judges heard arguments on whether to reinstate the executive order, while the Senate confirmed Betsy DeVos as Education Secretary in a historic tie-breaking vote.</p>

    <!-- TIMELINE -->
    <h2>Daily Chronology</h2>
    <div class="event">
        <span class="time">9:00 AM:</span> Received daily intelligence briefing at the White House.
    </div>
    <div class="event">
        <span class="time">9:30 AM:</span> Met with county sheriffs in the Roosevelt Room, where he made false claims about U.S. murder rates.
    </div>
    <div class="event">
        <span class="time">10:45 AM:</span> Met with Veterans Affairs officials in the Roosevelt Room.
    </div>
    <div class="event">
        <span class="time">1:30 PM:</span> Met with House Oversight Committee Chairman Rep. Jason Chaffetz (R-Utah).
    </div>
    <div class="event">
        <span class="time">3:00 PM:</span> Met with Secretary of State Rex Tillerson.
    </div>
    <div class="event">
        <span class="time">6:00 PM:</span> 9th Circuit Court of Appeals in San Francisco began hearing oral arguments on his travel ban executive order.
    </div>

    <!-- EXECUTIVE ACTIONS -->
    <h2>Legal Developments</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>The 9th Circuit Court of Appeals heard arguments on whether to reinstate Trump's travel ban executive order, which had been suspended by a federal judge in Seattle on February 3.</li>
        <li>The contentious hearing focused on whether the restraining order should remain in effect while legal challenges proceed.</li>
        <li>Judges questioned both sides on constitutional issues, including whether the ban unconstitutionally targeted Muslims.</li>
    </ul>

