    <!-- NOTABLE QUOTES -->
    <div class="pullquote">
        "The murder rate is the highest it's been I guess from forty-five to forty-seven years."
    </div>

    <!-- CABINET CONFIRMATIONS -->
    <h2>Cabinet Confirmations</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Betsy DeVos confirmed as Education Secretary:</strong> The Senate voted 51-50 to confirm DeVos, with Vice President Mike Pence casting the historic tie-breaking vote - the first time a VP broke a tie on a Cabinet nomination.</li>
        <li><strong>Jeff Sessions cleared procedural hurdle:</strong> His nomination for Attorney General advanced 52-47, with final confirmation expected the following day.</li>
        <li><strong>Neil Gorsuch meetings:</strong> Supreme Court nominee met with Sen. Dianne Feinstein, who described him as "impressive" and "legally very smart."</li>
    </ul>

    <!-- OTHER DEVELOPMENTS -->
    <h2>Other Notable Events</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Melania Trump libel case:</strong> First Lady settled lawsuit against Maryland blogger Webster Griffin Tarpley over false escort allegations, refiled case against Daily Mail in New York.</li>
        <li><strong>Ruth Bader Ginsburg comments:</strong> Supreme Court Justice spoke at Stanford University, expressing hope for less partisanship in Congress and support for changing the Electoral College system.</li>
        <li><strong>False murder rate claim:</strong> During meeting with sheriffs, Trump incorrectly stated that the U.S. murder rate was at a 47-year high, contradicting FBI statistics.</li>
    </ul>

    <!-- PRESS COVERAGE -->
    <h2>Press Coverage</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>CBS News:</strong> Provided comprehensive live coverage of the appeals court hearing on the travel ban and detailed analysis of the DeVos confirmation vote.</li>
        <li><strong>CNN:</strong> Featured the travel ban hearing and Cabinet confirmations as top stories in their "5 Things" daily briefing.</li>
        <li><strong>New York Times:</strong> Trump criticized the newspaper on Twitter, calling their reporting "total fiction" regarding internal White House operations.</li>
    </ul>

    <!-- HISTORICAL CONTEXT -->
    <h2>Historical Significance</h2>
    <p>February 7, 2017 marked a pivotal moment in Trump's early presidency, with his travel ban facing its first major judicial test while encountering unprecedented Senate resistance to his Cabinet nominees. The DeVos confirmation required the first-ever vice presidential tie-breaking vote for a Cabinet position, reflecting the deep partisan divisions surrounding Trump's appointments. The 9th Circuit arguments represented the administration's first major constitutional challenge, setting important precedents for executive power disputes that would characterize much of Trump's presidency.</p>

    <p>The day also highlighted Trump's tendency to make factually incorrect statements to law enforcement audiences, a pattern that would continue throughout his term. The convergence of legal challenges, Cabinet battles, and media disputes illustrated the contentious atmosphere that defined the administration's relationship with traditional institutions during its first weeks in office.</p>

